I think I am fine with moving to the latest, but this is different than we have done in the past. 
In the past we used the lowest schema version we needed (e.g. if we needed 1_2 for property x we would move to 1_2, but not 1_3). We did this based on guidance from Redfish. I think Redfish's thinking was, if it isn't needed to use 1_3 then don't use it (if you don't implement properties y and z in 1_3, don't use 1_3, client knows instantly you don't implement properties y and z). 

So when we move to a new Redfish release pack (e.g. DSP8010_2023.1), we will then use all of those new schemas ?

> I think I am fine with moving to the latest, but this is different than we have done in the past. 
> In the past we used the lowest schema version we needed (e.g. if we needed 1_2 for property x we would move to 1_2, but not 1_3). We did this based on guidance from Redfish. I think Redfish's thinking was, if it isn't needed to use 1_3 then don't use it (if you don't implement properties y and z in 1_3, don't use 1_3, client knows instantly you don't implement properties y and z). 
> 
> So when we move to a new Redfish release pack (e.g. DSP8010_2023.1), we will then use all of those new schemas ?

Yes, it would update on new schema packs.

Agreed, I'm conflicted on changing that policy, but I think in terms of tradeoffs, just staying on latest is the best.  The only other thing we could do is keep a list somewhere of explicit versions of the schema, but then we're back to people forgetting to update them.  I think DMTFs guidance is coming from a place of "less change is better", but if the change is automated, I'm not sure it hurts us.

Anywho, it sounds like you're ok with it.  I'm open to criticism of this, "null hypothesis" (ie leave it like it is), or other ideas that might be better.

I am also concerned we will have trouble moving to a new schema version because of some reason which blocks us from moving up the rest of the schemas...

Redfish has rules about backward compatibility, so that may be unlikely..? If it does happen and we can't fix it quickly, we could look at an explicit version for the problem schema. I am thinking of Redfish Validator errors we have hit in the past, the ones I am thinking of have to do with the property and not the schema version, so yeah, maybe that isn't much of a valid concern. I still do have some concerns about churn in the schema versions and going against what Redfish advised but as mentioned above I can get over those.

> I am also concerned we will have trouble moving to a new schema version because of some reason which blocks us from moving up the rest of the schemas...
> 
> Redfish has rules about backward compatibility, so that may be unlikely..? If it does happen and we can't fix it quickly, we could look at an explicit version for the problem schema.
> I am thinking of Redfish Validator errors we have hit in the past, the ones I am thinking of have to do with the property and not the schema version, so yeah, maybe that isn't much of a valid concern. I still do have some concerns about churn in the schema versions and going against what Redfish advised but as mentioned above I can get over those.


If it does happen in a certain case, we can always fall back to the old way we did versions, and hardcode the schema versions that fail, right?  Ideally, if we do hit that, we should just be fixing DMTF, but I think we still have the temporary trapdoor.

> If it does happen in a certain case, we can always fall back to the old way we did versions, and hardcode the schema versions that fail, right? Ideally, if we do hit that, we should just be fixing DMTF, but I think we still have the temporary trapdoor.

Agreed.

fixed all the includes I found.

Could we add all the schemas to this file?

The ones we are missing for example are AccelerationFunction, ...

This would make it line up with the Base Privilege Registry as well
I think we can generate all of them, but because we omit some of them, I don't think they can be added to the "schemas" array.  Would that work for you?

I dont mind creating my own schemas array in my own separate commit, but I do need all of the schemas (even the ones we omit) in an array somewhere. If it cant be done here, would you have any problems doing it in my own file?

IMO, I'd probably rather keep a single structure, with some sort of identifier like "omit from metadata".

FWIW, I think we're pretty close to just getting rid of the filtering altogether.  It's become less useful over time as we support more and more things.
Take a look at what I have now.  I think it accommodates what you need.
Yes it does.

I am in favor of this. I think the upside (not dealing with schema versions, no more failing the validator because the schema wasn't bumped, mismatching schema versions (e.g., Log Entry version A here and Log Entry version B there)) outweighs the negative (more work/chance at failing when moving to the new release pack, schemas becoming less independent, more churn in our schema versions). I would still prefer a list somewhere of explicit versions of the schemas we use, but I understand why you went this way (maintaining that list is going to be a pain, just like maintaining those individual schema versions today) also this has a few extra benefits - E.g. no more author failed to bump the schema.
Separately we could still get rid of this include list.
Agreed.

I didn't want to use the same source for both the test and the generation.  It doesn't make sense to test the output based on the code being tested.  For example, if something were broken, and the odata.type were set to empty string (""), this test would still pass, but the code would obviously be wrong.

I'm wondering about the handling when a property is either deprecated or added to the required list for a previously supported schema. Does DMTF ever make this type of change?

If so, it seems like moving up to a new Redfish level (like https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/66728) would require deeper understanding of the underlying schema changes and then subsequent code changes to handle anything deprecated or newly required. Is that desireable?

> I'm wondering about the handling when a property is either deprecated or added to the required list for a previously supported schema. Does DMTF ever make this type of change?

They do deprecate properties, but that functionally is just an annotation.  To my knowledge, they've never actually completely removed a property, so I don't think this changes anything functionally, unless Redfish were to actually remove something in the future (unlikely) in which case we'd see it right away.

> 
> If so, it seems like moving up to a new Redfish level (like https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/66728) would require deeper understanding of the underlying schema changes and then subsequent code changes to handle anything deprecated or newly required. Is that desireable?
Assuming we get rid of the include list, will the validator be able to pass without connection to dmtf.org? I.e. will the validator be able to pass offline?
It still should be able to, but we'll need to include the schemas in the image.
